-- Migration 012a: Implementation Plans — Batch A (IDs 1, 2, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9, 10, 12)
-- ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
BEGIN;

-- ── ID 1: Copyright Amendment Bill — Fair Use and Digital Access Reform ──────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    1,
    'The Copyright Amendment Bill (CAB) has been in limbo since President Ramaphosa referred it back to Parliament in 2020 citing constitutional concerns, and Parliament passed a revised version in 2022 that he returned unsigned in 2023. The path forward requires a targeted fix to the constitutional objections — primarily the Section 28 and 29 fair use provisions — through a narrow Section 75 amendment process, followed by Presidential assent. DTIC and the DTI Copyright Review Commission must simultaneously develop implementation guidelines for rightsholders and digital platform operators. The end-state is a fair use regime enabling digital education, libraries, parody, and transformative innovation while preserving creator compensation mechanisms. Operation Vulindlela tracks the CAB as a barrier to digital economy growth.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DTIC constitutes a joint legal-technical working group with the Department of Justice and Constitutional Development to address Section 28/29 constitutional objections identified in the Presidential referral; produce a revised CAB text for tabling in Parliament within 90 days","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Department of Trade, Industry and Competition (DTIC) / Department of Justice and Constitutional Development"},{"step":2,"description":"Table the revised CAB in the National Assembly as a Section 75 bill; refer to Portfolio Committee on Trade, Industry and Competition for accelerated public hearings with a 30-day comment period; prioritise rightsholders, publishers, universities, and digital platform operators","timeline":"Q3 2025","responsible_party":"DTIC / National Assembly Portfolio Committee on Trade, Industry and Competition"},{"step":3,"description":"Secure National Assembly and NCOP passage of the revised CAB; ensure consistency with the Performers Protection Amendment Bill to resolve ancillary performer rights gaps flagged in the 2020 Presidential referral","timeline":"Q4 2025","responsible_party":"Parliament / NCOP Select Committee on Trade and Industry"},{"step":4,"description":"Presidential assent; DTIC publishes subsidiary regulations under Section 22 of the Copyright Act 98 of 1978 (as amended) specifying fair use factors, orphan works procedure, and collecting society oversight rules","timeline":"Q1 2026","responsible_party":"Presidency / DTIC"},{"step":5,"description":"Companies and Intellectual Property Commission (CIPC) issues updated copyright registration guidelines; DTIC and DSI jointly publish a Digital Content Creation Policy framework for educational and creative sectors linking to the CAB fair use provisions","timeline":"Q2 2026","responsible_party":"CIPC / DTIC / Department of Science and Innovation (DSI)"},{"step":6,"description":"Establish a Copyright Tribunal under the amended Act with jurisdiction over collecting society disputes and fair use determinations; appoint Tribunal members and operationalise the secretariat within the IP Tribunal cluster","timeline":"Q2–Q3 2026","responsible_party":"Department of Justice / DTIC / CIPC"},{"step":7,"description":"Two-year post-enactment review: DTIC commissions independent study of fair use uptake across education, creative industries, and digital platforms; benchmarks against US Copyright Office fair use data and South Korea experience; report to Cabinet","timeline":"Q1 2028","responsible_party":"DTIC / DSI / CIPC"}]',
    '18–24 months from tabling of revised bill to full implementation (Q2 2025–Q1 2027)',
    'R45 million over 3 years: Copyright Tribunal establishment (~R25m), CIPC implementation and regulatory guidelines (~R12m), review commission operations (~R8m)',
    'Amendment to Copyright Act 98 of 1978 (primary); Performers Protection Amendment Bill (companion bill, must pass concurrently); Copyright Tribunal Rules (subsidiary legislation under Copyright Act Section 29A)',
    'The revised CAB must directly address the three categories of Presidential constitutional objection: (1) overly broad fair use standard in Section 12B lacking sufficient determinacy; (2) Section 20(1) moral rights provisions potentially incompatible with Section 22 copyright transfer; (3) Section 28(1) educational exception potentially conflicting with Berne Convention three-step test obligations under Section 231 of the Constitution. The fix should narrow fair use to a structured four-factor test (as per US 17 USC §107) rather than an open-ended enumeration. Section 75 bill classification means NCOP can only delay, not block, passage.',
    'The CAB has survived two presidential referrals and two parliamentary sessions — political will exists across the GNU to resolve it. DA and ANC both support digital economy reform. The primary resistance comes from major collecting societies (SAMRO, DALRO, RISA) and publishing houses (Pearson, Oxford University Press SA) over royalty impact. DTIC must negotiate a transitional collecting society compensation mechanism to neutralise industry opposition. Operation Vulindlela tracking provides Presidency-level political impetus. International trade pressure from the US (USTR Section 301 Watch List) is a complicating factor that DIRCO must manage diplomatically.',
    'United States 17 USC §107 (1976, codified fair use doctrine): four-factor test enabling transformative use in education, commentary, parody, and research — the direct model for SA''s approach. South Korea Copyright Act 2011 amendment introduced a US-style fair use clause, reducing educational content licensing costs by 60% within five years. European Union Directive 2019/790 on Copyright in the Digital Single Market introduced mandatory exceptions for text and data mining, education, and cultural heritage — an alternative model for the NCOP to consider. Israel Copyright Act 2007 introduced fair use as part of an IP modernisation package that preceded its OECD accession process.'
);

-- ── ID 2: Competition Commission Digital Markets Inquiry ──────────────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    2,
    'The Competition Commission''s Online Intermediation Platforms Market Inquiry (OIPMI), launched formally in 2022, targets Google, Meta, Takealot, and Uber operating in SA. Under the Competition Act 89 of 1998 (as amended by the Competition Amendment Act 2018), a market inquiry can result in remedial action without a finding of prohibited conduct. The OIPMI must conclude with implementable remedies by 2025–2026, and DTIC must simultaneously table a dedicated Digital Markets Act to create ex ante regulation of designated gatekeepers — a structural gap the market inquiry cannot fill alone. The Competition Tribunal will adjudicate any remedy disputes. DSBD has a parallel interest in protecting small business sellers on Takealot and other platforms under the buyer power provisions of the Competition Amendment Act.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"Competition Commission completes OIPMI provisional report and circulates to affected parties (Google, Meta, Takealot, Uber) for response; public release of provisional findings with a 30-day comment window","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Competition Commission"},{"step":2,"description":"Competition Commission publishes final OIPMI report with binding remedial action recommendations; remedies to address: (a) search self-preferencing by Google, (b) data portability obligations for Meta and Google, (c) most-favoured-nation clause restrictions for Takealot, (d) surge pricing transparency for Uber","timeline":"Q4 2025","responsible_party":"Competition Commission"},{"step":3,"description":"DTIC tables a Digital Markets Bill in Parliament, designating gatekeepers with obligations for interoperability, data access, non-discrimination, and advance notification of acquisitions; modelled on EU Digital Markets Act (DMA) 2022 but calibrated for SA market concentration","timeline":"Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / Competition Commission / National Treasury"},{"step":4,"description":"Competition Tribunal processes any appeals against OIPMI remedial action; Competition Commission enforces interim compliance measures pending Tribunal resolution","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q2 2026","responsible_party":"Competition Commission / Competition Tribunal"},{"step":5,"description":"Parliament passes Digital Markets Bill; DTIC establishes a Digital Markets Unit within the Competition Commission with dedicated economic and technical capacity; appoint Digital Markets Commissioner as a specialist position","timeline":"Q3–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"Parliament / DTIC / Competition Commission"},{"step":6,"description":"Competition Commission publishes gatekeeper designation criteria and designates initial platforms (Google Search, Google Play, Meta Platforms, Takealot Marketplace) as gatekeepers with 12-month compliance timelines","timeline":"Q1 2027","responsible_party":"Competition Commission / DTIC"},{"step":7,"description":"Annual Digital Markets Compliance Review: Competition Commission publishes compliance scorecards for designated gatekeepers; DSBD tracks outcomes for small business sellers and reports to Portfolio Committee on Trade and DSBD","timeline":"Annual from Q1 2028","responsible_party":"Competition Commission / DSBD"}]',
    'OIPMI final report by Q4 2025; Digital Markets Act by Q4 2026; gatekeeper compliance by Q1 2028',
    'R180 million over 4 years: Competition Commission Digital Markets Unit capacity (R35m/year), OIPMI process and legal costs (~R25m), Digital Markets Bill drafting (~R8m)',
    'Competition Amendment Act 18 of 2018 (already enacted — provides market inquiry and buyer power tools); Digital Markets Bill (new primary legislation required); Amendment to Competition Act 89 of 1998 to add designated gatekeeper provisions and advance merger notification threshold for acquisitions below existing thresholds',
    'The Digital Markets Bill should be structured as an amendment to the Competition Act adding a new Chapter on Digital Markets, rather than standalone legislation, to leverage existing Competition Tribunal jurisdiction and enforcement infrastructure. Key provisions: gatekeeper designation criteria (following EC Article 3 DMA thresholds, adapted to SA market size), interoperability obligations, data portability, self-preferencing prohibition, and an expedited Competition Tribunal review track for digital markets disputes. The buyer power provisions in Competition Amendment Act Section 8(4) can be activated immediately for Takealot seller relationships via Regulation by DTIC — no new legislation required for this element.',
    'Strong support from DSBD, which has received extensive complaints from small business sellers on Takealot. The Competition Commission has political independence under the Competition Act and has demonstrated willingness to act against large platforms (Google Android investigation, 2022). The DA supports digital markets regulation as pro-consumer and pro-competition. Large platform operators (Google, Meta) are actively lobbying against ex ante regulation; their primary argument is that SA''s digital economy is nascent and over-regulation will deter investment. National Treasury is broadly supportive but will require a regulatory impact assessment demonstrating net economic benefit. The OIPMI provides the evidentiary foundation that neutralises the ''no evidence of harm'' argument.',
    'European Union Digital Markets Act (DMA), effective May 2023: designated six gatekeepers (Alphabet, Amazon, Apple, ByteDance, Meta, Microsoft) with compliance obligations; preliminary evidence shows 15–20% improvement in app store competition. United Kingdom Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) Digital Markets, Competition and Consumers Act 2024: strategic market status designation for Google and Apple, with enforceable conduct requirements. Australia ACCC Digital Platform Services Inquiry (2022): produced mandatory news media bargaining code (News Media and Digital Platforms Mandatory Bargaining Code Act 2021) generating A$200 million+ in payments to Australian news publishers — a model for SA''s media sector. Kenya Competition Authority market inquiry into digital lending platforms (2023) provides a developing-economy precedent.'
);

-- ── ID 4: AfCFTA Implementation and Intra-African Trade Expansion ─────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    4,
    'South Africa ratified the AfCFTA in 2019 and submitted its first tariff offer. However, actual implementation — operationalising the schedules, aligning rules of origin, and connecting SA exporters to the AfCFTA Digital Trade Protocol — requires a dedicated national implementation architecture. DTIC, National Treasury, and ITAC must coordinate tariff schedule operationalisation, while the dtic companies (ECDC, IDC, SEDA) support exporter readiness. The AfCFTA Secretariat''s Guided Trade Initiative (GTI) has demonstrated proof-of-concept trades; SA must scale its participation. Critically, SA''s non-tariff barriers — port inefficiency, SPS standards divergence, and cross-border payment friction — are larger constraints than tariffs, and Operation Vulindlela''s trade facilitation workstream must be extended to the AfCFTA context.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DTIC establishes a dedicated AfCFTA National Implementation Committee (NIC) with representation from ITAC, National Treasury, DIRCO, SARS Customs, DALRRD (SPS), and DFFE; NIC publishes a National AfCFTA Implementation Plan covering the 3-year priority agenda","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Department of Trade, Industry and Competition (DTIC) / DIRCO"},{"step":2,"description":"ITAC finalises and gazetted SA''s Phase 1 tariff schedule operationalisation for goods traded with AfCFTA parties; SARS Customs implements the preferential tariff codes in its systems; publish Tariff Implementation Notice in Government Gazette","timeline":"Q3 2025","responsible_party":"ITAC / SARS Customs / National Treasury"},{"step":3,"description":"DTIC and DALRRD negotiate mutual recognition of SPS standards with ECOWAS and EAC blocs for SA''s top agricultural export categories (citrus, wine, deciduous fruit, processed meats); publish MRA frameworks within 18 months","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q1 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / Department of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development (DALRRD) / DIRCO"},{"step":4,"description":"IDC and SEDA launch an AfCFTA Exporter Readiness Fund (R500m capitalisation from IDC balance sheet) providing concessional trade finance, market intelligence, and standards compliance support for SA exporters targeting 10 new African markets; prioritise agro-processing, automotive components, and business services","timeline":"Q4 2025","responsible_party":"Industrial Development Corporation (IDC) / SEDA / DTIC"},{"step":5,"description":"SARB and National Treasury join the AfCFTA Pan-African Payment and Settlement System (PAPSS) as an active participant bank; pilot rand-denominated settlement for SA''s five largest African bilateral trade relationships (Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Zambia, Kenya, Ghana)","timeline":"Q2 2026","responsible_party":"South African Reserve Bank / National Treasury"},{"step":6,"description":"SA ratifies and domesticates the AfCFTA Digital Trade Protocol (signed 2023); DTIC issues implementing regulations on cross-border data flows, electronic signatures, and digital payments compatible with POPIA and the Electronic Communications and Transactions Act","timeline":"Q3 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / SARB / Department of Communications and Digital Technologies (DCDT)"},{"step":7,"description":"Annual AfCFTA Trade Performance Report: NIC publishes intra-African export volumes, tariff utilisation rates, and NTB reduction scorecard; submit to Cabinet and Parliament; benchmark against AfCFTA Secretariat GTI targets","timeline":"Annual from Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / ITAC / NIC"}]',
    '3-year priority implementation window (2025–2028); full liberalisation schedule extends to 2035+',
    'R850 million over 3 years: IDC Exporter Readiness Fund (R500m IDC balance sheet), NIC secretariat and technical assistance (R80m from DTIC), SARS Customs system upgrades (R120m), SPS standards harmonisation programme (R150m from DALRRD and development finance)',
    'AfCFTA Agreement (ratified — no new primary legislation required for tariff schedules); AfCFTA Digital Trade Protocol domestication (requires implementing regulations under Electronic Communications and Transactions Act 25 of 2002 and POPIA); SARB participation in PAPSS (administrative arrangement under SARB Act — no new legislation required)',
    'SA''s AfCFTA tariff schedule is already submitted and ratified. Implementation regulations under the IECTA for digital trade protocol domestication will require a DTIC regulation published under Section 90 of the ECT Act. SPS mutual recognition agreements are executive instruments — no parliamentary process required. PAPSS participation by SARB requires a Board decision under SARB Act Section 10.',
    'Strong political will from DIRCO and the Presidency — AfCFTA is a flagship African agenda item for SA. The ANC has championed AfCFTA; the DA is supportive provided it does not undermine AGOA or bilateral EU trade interests. COSATU and NUMSA are cautious about import competition from lower-wage African producers in textiles and electronics — DTIC must produce sectoral impact assessments demonstrating net job creation. The main implementation risk is not political resistance but institutional coordination failure across DTIC, ITAC, DALRRD, and SARS. Operation Vulindlela''s mandate should be formally extended to AfCFTA implementation coordination.',
    'Rwanda AfCFTA GTI pilot (2022): first formally traded AfCFTA goods (pharmaceuticals and other goods) demonstrated the settlement and customs clearance mechanism. Ethiopia-Kenya bilateral trade under AfCFTA preferential rates (2023) reduced effective tariffs by 12 percentage points on processed food exports. Mauritius, ranked SA''s top African trading partner by share of AfCFTA-eligible exports, achieved 85% tariff utilisation rate by 2024 through a dedicated export facilitation desk — a model for SEDA/IDC exporter readiness support. ECOWAS common external tariff (1975–2015 evolution) provides lessons on managing domestic industry adjustment during tariff liberalisation.'
);

-- ── ID 5: EV White Paper — Managed Automotive Transition ─────────────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    5,
    'The South African Electric Vehicles White Paper (2023), led by DTIC, commits SA to becoming a competitive destination for EV manufacturing while managing the transition from internal combustion engine (ICE) production. The centrepiece is an EV incentive framework embedded within the Automotive Production and Development Programme (APDP) Phase 3 (2026–2035), supplemented by EV-specific component localisation targets and a battery value chain development strategy. SA must secure OEM investment decisions from BMW (Rosslyn), Toyota (Prospecton), and Volkswagen (Uitenhage) for EV-platform mandates before their 2027 capital allocation cycles. NUMSA and the automotive supply chain have negotiated a Just Transition framework under the Automotive Masterplan. The DMRE''s grid strengthening and REIPPPP tariff competitiveness are necessary enabling conditions.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DTIC gazetted EV White Paper implementing framework as a formal policy statement; publish the EV Incentive Programme term sheet for OEM comment, specifying production volume allowances, local content requirements, and battery integration targets under APDP Phase 3","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Department of Trade, Industry and Competition (DTIC)"},{"step":2,"description":"DTIC and ITAC submit APDP Phase 3 framework to Cabinet for approval; Phase 3 framework includes a dedicated EV Production Incentive (EVPI) with tiered duty credit certificates for vehicles manufactured with 40%+ local content and qualifying battery pack integration","timeline":"Q3 2025","responsible_party":"DTIC / ITAC / National Treasury"},{"step":3,"description":"Conclude bilateral investment incentive agreements with BMW SA (Rosslyn), Toyota SA (Prospecton), and Volkswagen SA (Uitenhage) specifying EV model mandates, capital investment commitments, and EVPI utilisation; secure at least two OEM EV platform commitments by December 2026","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / Presidency Investment and Infrastructure Office"},{"step":4,"description":"DSI and DTIC establish a Battery Value Chain Programme under the SA National Roadmap for Energy Storage: support CSIR cathode material research, incentivise a battery assembly facility through IDC industrial financing, and develop a critical minerals beneficiation linkage (manganese, vanadium) with DMRE","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"Department of Science and Innovation (DSI) / DTIC / IDC / DMRE"},{"step":5,"description":"DTPS and DMRE publish a national EV charging infrastructure plan: 1,000 public charging stations across 9 provinces by 2028, with municipal integration requirements; partner with Eskom and municipalities on grid-ready EV charging standards (SANS 1935)","timeline":"Q4 2025–Q2 2028","responsible_party":"Department of Transport (DOT) / DMRE / Eskom / Municipalities"},{"step":6,"description":"NUMSA and DTIC finalise the Automotive Just Transition Fund: R2 billion capitalisation from DTIC and IDC for worker retraining (through merSETA), supplier diversification support, and community transition assistance in Rosslyn, Prospecton, and Uitenhage corridors","timeline":"Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / IDC / merSETA / NUMSA"},{"step":7,"description":"Annual Automotive Masterplan EV scorecard: track OEM EV production volumes, local content attainment, battery value chain investment, and employment levels; report to Portfolio Committee on Trade, Industry and Competition and to Cabinet Economic Cluster","timeline":"Annual from Q1 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / ITAC"}]',
    '2025–2035 (APDP Phase 3 horizon); critical OEM investment decisions by end-2026; charging infrastructure by 2028',
    'R12 billion in APDP Phase 3 incentives (foregone duty and EVPI) over 10 years; R2 billion Automotive Just Transition Fund; R1.5 billion charging infrastructure co-investment (public-private); battery programme R800m (DSI/IDC); total public commitment approximately R5 billion over 5 years',
    'No new primary legislation required for APDP Phase 3 EV incentive; International Trade Administration Act (ITAA) tariff schedule amendment for EVPI duty credits; National Energy Regulator Amendment Act for EV charging grid standards; Road Traffic Act amendments for EV type approval (NRTA administered by DOT)',
    'APDP Phase 3 is administered through ITAC under the ITAA — Cabinet approval and ITAC schedule gazette notification are the key procedural steps, not parliamentary legislation. EV type approval amendments to NRTA regulations require DOT regulation published in Government Gazette. Grid connection standards for EV charging (SANS 1935) are administered by SABS — administrative process. Just Transition Fund is structured as an IDC facility, not a statutory fund, so no parliamentary process is required.',
    'Strong cross-party support: automotive sector employment (113,000 direct, 400,000 indirect) creates broad political protection. NUMSA is cautious but engaged in the Just Transition negotiation — their buy-in is essential and achievable. OEM pressure on government is the primary driver of urgency: BMW, Toyota, and VW have all signalled they need policy certainty before their 2027 capital allocation decisions. National Treasury is supportive of APDP continuity but will scrutinise the cost-per-job ratio of EV incentives. GNU dynamics are favourable — both ANC and DA support industrial policy for employment preservation.',
    'Thailand Board of Investment EV incentive package (2022): excise tax reduction, duty-free battery import, and production grants attracted BYD, Great Wall Motor, and Foxconn to establish EV manufacturing — 30,000 EV units produced by 2024. Germany KfW Just Transition Fund (EUR 1 billion, 2021): supported ICE component suppliers pivoting to EV parts, protecting 45,000 jobs in Baden-Württemberg and Bavaria. Morocco AMICA automotive incentives: integrated EV supply chain strategy attracted Stellantis and Renault EV platform mandates, generating EUR 1.5 billion in EV exports by 2023. Indonesia EV White Paper (2021): local content requirements of 40% for government EV procurement drove battery assembly investment by LG and Hyundai.'
);

-- ── ID 6: Green Hydrogen Commercialisation Strategy ──────────────────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    6,
    'South Africa''s Hydrogen Society Roadmap (2021) and the Green Hydrogen Commercialisation Strategy target 10 GW of electrolysis capacity by 2035, positioning SA as a major global green hydrogen exporter via the Boegoebaai port development in the Northern Cape. The strategy links renewable energy abundance (solar irradiance 5.5–6 kWh/m²/day, wind resources in Northern and Western Cape) to hydrogen production economics and export logistics. Three anchor projects are central: the Boegoebaai Green Hydrogen Export Hub, the Limpopo Platinum Valley Green Hydrogen Corridor (PGM-based fuel cells), and the Western Cape hydrogen mobility pilot. National Treasury, DTIC, DSI, and DMRE must align fiscal incentives, and the Presidential Climate Commission provides the governance framework. Germany''s H2Global auction mechanism has committed EUR 900 million to purchase SA green hydrogen and derivatives.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DMRE and DSI publish the Green Hydrogen Fiscal Incentive Framework: production tax credit of R2/kg for certified green hydrogen, investment allowance of 150% on electrolysis and renewable energy assets linked to hydrogen production, and a Renewable Energy Hydrogen Purchase Agreement guarantee facility administered by DBSA","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Department of Mineral Resources and Energy (DMRE) / Department of Science and Innovation (DSI) / National Treasury"},{"step":2,"description":"IDC and DBSA capitalise the Green Hydrogen Infrastructure Fund with R5 billion (R2bn IDC, R2bn DBSA, R1bn DTIC incentive window): fund Boegoebaai port infrastructure (storage, pipeline, loading facility), grid connection costs for Northern Cape electrolysis parks, and first-mover electrolysis project finance","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q1 2026","responsible_party":"IDC / Development Bank of Southern Africa (DBSA) / Northern Cape Provincial Government / DTIC"},{"step":3,"description":"Conclude the H2Global offtake framework agreement with the German government (BMWi): formalise auction schedule for SA-origin green hydrogen derivatives (ammonia, methanol); establish SA''s Green Hydrogen Certification Standard (aligned to CertifHy and EU Delegated Regulation 2023/1185) to qualify for EU import incentives","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DIRCO / DMRE / DSI / South African Bureau of Standards (SABS)"},{"step":4,"description":"Boegoebaai Phase 1 infrastructure: conclude Special Development Zone designation for Boegoebaai under the Special Economic Zones Act; TRANSNET Ports Authority and the Department of Public Works approve port development plan; initiate EIA process under NEMA","timeline":"Q4 2025–Q2 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / Transnet / Department of Public Works and Infrastructure / DFFE"},{"step":5,"description":"Limpopo Platinum Valley Green Hydrogen Corridor: DMRE issues Hydrogen Production Facility licences under the Petroleum Products Act (amended to include hydrogen); DSI and Implats/Anglo Platinum co-fund a PEM electrolysis demonstration plant at scale (10 MW); target first green hydrogen from PGM-catalyst plant by Q4 2027","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DMRE / DSI / Implats / Anglo Platinum"},{"step":6,"description":"Western Cape Green Hydrogen Mobility Pilot: City of Cape Town, PRASA, and Golden Arrow Bus Service deploy 50 hydrogen fuel cell buses and 3 fuelling stations; establish regulatory framework under the National Land Transport Act for hydrogen vehicles","timeline":"Q3 2026–Q4 2028","responsible_party":"Western Cape Provincial Government / City of Cape Town / Department of Transport"},{"step":7,"description":"Green Hydrogen Investment Conference (annual): DTIC hosts an international investment forum tracking electrolyser capacity commitments, export contracts, and job creation in the hydrogen value chain; publish Green Hydrogen Progress Report to Cabinet and Parliament","timeline":"Annual from Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / Presidential Climate Commission / DMRE"}]',
    '2025–2035 for 10 GW target; Boegoebaai Phase 1 operational by 2030; first export shipments by 2029',
    'Total public investment mobilisation target: R150 billion over 10 years (R5bn public infrastructure fund, remainder private and blended; H2Global EUR 900m commitment; JET-IP Just Energy Transition Partnership green hydrogen window)',
    'Petroleum Products Act 120 of 1977 (amendment to include hydrogen as a regulated product); National Environmental Management Act (NEMA) for Boegoebaai EIA; Special Economic Zones Act 16 of 2014 (Boegoebaai SDZ designation); Electricity Regulation Act (generation licences for dedicated hydrogen RE capacity); National Land Transport Act (hydrogen vehicle type approval)',
    'The Petroleum Products Act amendment to include hydrogen is being drafted within DMRE — the bill should be introduced in 2025 as part of the broader energy laws amendment programme. Boegoebaai SDZ designation requires a Ministerial determination under SEZ Act Section 23 followed by Government Gazette notice — no parliamentary process. The H2 certification standard is an administrative standard (SANS/SABS process) not requiring legislation. National Treasury''s Section 12B tax allowance for renewable energy assets can be extended to electrolysis by SARS interpretation note — no legislative amendment required initially.',
    'Strong political support: green hydrogen is a GNU priority with cross-party backing. The JET-IP International Partners Group (EU, UK, US, France, Germany) has committed USD 8.5 billion including a green hydrogen development window — this creates strong external political incentives. DMRE Minister must navigate coal industry interests (Minerals Council) but green hydrogen is positioned as additive to, not substitutive of, the minerals sector. The Northern Cape provincial government is highly supportive of Boegoebaai as an economic development anchor. NUMSA''s Just Transition concerns must be addressed by ensuring local content in electrolysis manufacturing and construction.',
    'Chile National Green Hydrogen Strategy (2020): 5 GW electrolysis target by 2025; first green ammonia export shipment to Germany in 2023; HIF Global Haru Oni fuel project demonstrates the export pathway. Germany H2Global mechanism (2021): EUR 900 million auction mechanism for green hydrogen imports; SA is a priority supply partner. Namibia Green Hydrogen Strategy (2022): Hyphen Hydrogen Energy project (3 GW, USD 10 billion) in the Tsau //Khaeb National Park — a direct competitor demonstrating that African green hydrogen is commercially viable. Morocco Green Hydrogen Roadmap (2021): Hydrogen Integration Cluster in Dakhla targeting 3 GW by 2030, with direct pipeline to Spain — demonstrates the export infrastructure model SA must replicate at Boegoebaai.'
);

-- ── ID 7: Steel and Metal Fabrication Master Plan ────────────────────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    7,
    'The Steel and Metal Fabrication Master Plan (2021–2030) is a multi-party social compact between DTIC, ArcelorMittal SA (AMSA), the Steel and Engineering Industries Federation (SEIFSA), NUMSA, and downstream metal fabricators. Its core challenge is that AMSA''s Vanderbijlpark and Newcastle works are structurally uncompetitive at prevailing energy prices and global steel prices — the Newport Works closure in 2023 destroyed 3,500 direct jobs. The survival of primary flat steel production depends on competitive electricity prices (target: industrial tariff below R1.50/kWh), import protection calibrated to avoid downstream cost increases, and committed infrastructure procurement channelling public capex through local steel. The Masterplan''s 30,000 job creation target requires downstream beneficiation growth in automotive components, capital equipment, and construction materials, not just upstream recovery.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DTIC, National Treasury, and Eskom formalise an Industrial Energy Price Compact for strategic energy-intensive industries: negotiate a cost-reflective but internationally competitive tariff for AMSA Vanderbijlpark and Newcastle under NERSA''s Eskom Tariff Methodology; target industrial tariff below R1.50/kWh by 2026","timeline":"Q2 2025–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DTIC / National Treasury / Eskom / NERSA"},{"step":2,"description":"ITAC reviews and recalibrates flat steel import duties (HTS 7208–7212) to prevent dumping from China, Turkey, and Ukraine while limiting cost pass-through to downstream manufacturers; implement a rolling quarterly ITAC monitoring mechanism with automatic review triggers","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"ITAC / DTIC"},{"step":3,"description":"Presidency and National Treasury formalise a local steel content requirement for all public infrastructure procurement above R100 million: amend the PPPFA Regulations 2022 to require 70% local steel content in PRASA, Transnet, and Eskom infrastructure contracts","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q1 2026","responsible_party":"National Treasury / DTIC / Office of the Presidency"},{"step":4,"description":"DTIC activates the Downstream Steel Beneficiation Fund (R1.5 billion IDC facility): provide industrial finance for capital equipment manufacturers, structural steel fabricators, and engineering component producers to expand capacity and export capability into Africa","timeline":"Q4 2025","responsible_party":"IDC / DTIC / SEIFSA"},{"step":5,"description":"DSI and DTIC launch a Steel Innovation Programme: R200 million over 5 years for applied research in green steelmaking (direct reduced iron using green hydrogen), advanced high-strength steel for automotive, and additive manufacturing applications; partnership with CSIR and AMSA R&D division","timeline":"Q1 2026","responsible_party":"DSI / DTIC / CSIR / AMSA"},{"step":6,"description":"NUMSA, SEIFSA, DTIC, and AMSA conclude a Labour Peace and Investment Compact under the Masterplan: formalise wage settlement framework, skills development commitments through merSETA (2,000 apprenticeships/year), and a mutual commitment to five-year operational continuity for Vanderbijlpark","timeline":"Q2 2026","responsible_party":"NUMSA / SEIFSA / DTIC / AMSA / merSETA"},{"step":7,"description":"Annual Steel Masterplan Review: DTIC publishes a public scorecard covering AMSA production volumes, energy cost attainment, import duty utilisation, local content procurement, downstream employment, and export revenues; report to Portfolio Committee on Trade, Industry and Competition","timeline":"Annual from Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / ITAC / IDC"}]',
    '2025–2030 (Masterplan period); energy compact by Q4 2025; PPPFA local content amendment by Q1 2026',
    'R3.5 billion public and development finance commitment over 5 years: IDC Downstream Beneficiation Fund (R1.5bn), DSI/DTIC Steel Innovation Programme (R200m), Eskom industrial tariff revenue foregone (estimated R800m/year for AMSA facilities), PPPFA local content premium on public procurement (~R1bn/year)',
    'Preferential Procurement Regulations (amendment under PPPFA 5 of 2000) for local steel content requirement; ITAC tariff schedule adjustments under ITAA (administrative, no legislation); Industrial Development Corporation Act (IDC facility authorisation — administrative); possible amendment to the Competition Act exemption for AMSA restructuring agreements',
    'PPPFA Regulation amendment is the critical legislative instrument. National Treasury publishes PPPFA Regulations under Section 5 of the PPPFA — Cabinet approval is required, not parliamentary vote. The 70% local steel content designation would be added to the Designated Sectors list under Regulation 8. ITAC tariff adjustments are gazette notices under the ITAA — the ITAC Board recommends, the Minister of Trade, Industry and Competition approves. AMSA restructuring arrangements may require a Competition Act Section 10 exemption if they involve pricing coordination with downstream buyers.',
    'Moderate-to-high feasibility within the GNU. ANC has historically protected primary steel as a strategic industry; DA supports industrial policy that is market-correcting rather than market-distorting and will scrutinise the PPPFA amendment for WTO consistency. NUMSA is a strong advocate for Masterplan implementation. The key political risk is AMSA''s shareholder (ArcelorMittal Global) — if the energy compact and import protection are insufficient, they may proceed with further divestment. National Treasury will require rigorous cost-benefit analysis of foregone tariff revenue against employment preservation.',
    'Turkey Steel Modernisation Programme (2015–2022): combination of anti-dumping duties on Chinese steel and energy price support for electric arc furnace producers enabled Turkish steel exports to grow from 18 million tonnes to 27 million tonnes, making Turkey the world''s eighth largest steel producer. India Steel Scrap Recycling Policy (2019): mandatory local scrap content rules for downstream steel users drove investment in scrap processing infrastructure and reduced import dependence. Japan METI Steel Industry Strategy (2021): government-coordinated capacity rationalisation combined with green hydrogen steelmaking R&D investment (COURSE50 programme) — the closest precedent for SA''s dual objective of immediate survival and long-term decarbonisation. Brazil CSN and USIMINAS state-coordinated rationalisation (2016): IDC-style development bank financing (BNDES) for facility upgrades combined with public procurement preferences maintained primary steel capacity through a commodity price trough.'
);

-- ── ID 8: Retail-CTFL Master Plan ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    8,
    'The Retail-Clothing, Textile, Footwear and Leather (R-CTFL) Master Plan (2019–2030), signed as a social compact between DTIC, SACTWU, the SA Clothing and Textile Workers Union (SACTWU), retailer signatories (Woolworths, Edcon, Truworths, TFG, Foschini), and the National Bargaining Council for the Clothing Manufacturing Industry, commits to raising local market share from 44% to 65% by 2030 and creating 121,000 new jobs. The strategy has three pillars: (1) local procurement commitments from retailer signatories; (2) skills development through merSETA and the NBC; and (3) trade protection via ITAC anti-dumping duties on Chinese imports. Progress has been below target — local market share reached only 46% by 2023 — requiring accelerated enforcement of retailer commitments and stronger anti-dumping action on Chinese fast fashion and footwear.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DTIC convenes the R-CTFL Masterplan Steering Committee to conduct a mid-term review (2025): audit retailer local sourcing commitments against contractual targets; identify non-compliant signatories and institute remedial action protocols including potential exclusion from AGOA-linked benefits and DTIC support programmes","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Department of Trade, Industry and Competition (DTIC) / R-CTFL Steering Committee"},{"step":2,"description":"ITAC initiates a comprehensive anti-dumping and safeguard review on Chinese clothing, textile, and footwear imports (HTS 61–64): apply for provisional safeguard measures under the WTO Safeguards Agreement where import surge evidence is documented; publish ITAC investigation findings and duty recommendations within 12 months","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"ITAC / DTIC / South African Textile and Clothing Industry (SATCI)"},{"step":3,"description":"DSBD and the DTIC Enterprise and Supplier Development (ESD) desk establish an R-CTFL SME Supplier Development Programme: provide concessional finance (IDC R800m facility), factory upgrades, and lean manufacturing training to 200 SMME clothing and textile manufacturers targeting retailer local supplier qualification","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q1 2027","responsible_party":"DSBD / IDC / merSETA / DTIC ESD"},{"step":4,"description":"merSETA and the NBC design and roll out a Clothing Manufacturing Skills Programme: 5,000 new operator apprenticeships per year through accredited training centres in Cape Town (Bellville), Durban (Phoenix), and Johannesburg (Cleveland); publish annual skills pipeline report","timeline":"Q3 2025 (intake) — ongoing","responsible_party":"merSETA / NBC / DTIC"},{"step":5,"description":"DTIC and SARS Customs implement an enhanced import monitoring system for clothing and footwear: mandatory advance cargo declarations for textile shipments from China, Bangladesh, and Vietnam; deployment of Customs Risk Engine profiling for under-invoiced textile imports; quarterly ITAC smuggling report","timeline":"Q4 2025","responsible_party":"SARS Customs / ITAC / DTIC"},{"step":6,"description":"Retailer Local Content Scorecard (public): DTIC publishes annual local sourcing performance data for all Masterplan signatories; introduce a voluntary R-CTFL Made in SA certification label administered by SABS for qualifying locally manufactured garments","timeline":"Q2 2026 (first publication)","responsible_party":"DTIC / SABS / SA Retail Council"},{"step":7,"description":"R-CTFL Export Diversification Programme: IDC and SEDA co-fund market entry for SA clothing manufacturers into AfCFTA-accessible markets (Kenya, Nigeria, Ethiopia); target R2 billion in African clothing exports by 2028; partner with SA Fashion Week and the Design Institute of SA for brand positioning","timeline":"Q1 2026–Q4 2028","responsible_party":"IDC / SEDA / DTIC / SA Fashion Week"}]',
    '2025–2030 (Masterplan period); critical interventions front-loaded to 2025–2026; 65% local market share by 2030',
    'R2.5 billion public and development finance over 5 years: IDC SME facility (R800m), merSETA skills programme (R400m/year levy-funded), SARS Customs system upgrade (R200m), ITAC investigation costs (R30m), export programme (R150m IDC/SEDA)',
    'ITAC anti-dumping and safeguard duties (administered under ITAA and WTO Safeguards Agreement — no new legislation required); amendment to PPPFA Regulations to designate clothing and uniforms as designated sectors (extend and strengthen existing designation)',
    'ITAC safeguard investigations are conducted under the International Trade Administration Act 71 of 2002 and the WTO Agreement on Safeguards — administrative process. The existing PPPFA designation of clothing and textiles under Regulation 8 already exists; strengthening it requires a regulation amendment by National Treasury. SARS Customs advance cargo declaration system can be implemented under Section 38 of the Customs and Excise Act 91 of 1964 — no parliamentary process required. The NBC binding determination on wages in the clothing sector is issued under the Labour Relations Act — DTIC and Department of Employment and Labour must coordinate.',
    'Moderate feasibility with strong sectoral political support. ANC is committed to the Masterplan as a black economic empowerment and manufacturing employment priority. SACTWU has significant union political leverage through COSATU. Retailer signatories (Woolworths, TFG, Foschini) are motivated by reputational and regulatory pressure; smaller non-signatories and the informal market remain outside the compact. Chinese fast fashion competition (Shein, Temu) represents a new digital import channel that is structurally difficult to regulate through ITAC — DTIC needs a digital customs framework as a companion measure. DA will support skills and enterprise development but may scrutinise anti-dumping measures for consumer price impact.',
    'Ethiopia Hawassa Industrial Park (2016): AGOA-linked export processing zone attracted H&M, PVH, and Guess manufacturing — generated 30,000 garment jobs within 3 years; demonstrates that targeted industrial zone development can rapidly build a textile export base. Bangladesh BGMEA (Bangladesh Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association) industry compact with government (2014): skills development levy-funded training of 1.2 million garment workers underpins Bangladesh''s position as the world''s second largest garment exporter. Portugal textile sector revitalisation (2010–2018): combination of export marketing, design upgrading, and anti-dumping protection from Chinese imports raised Portuguese textile exports by 40% and created 25,000 jobs — a European precedent for mid-income country sector recovery. Morocco Textile Plan (2014–2020): EUR 2 billion investment in fashion-forward production, EU proximity advantage, and fast fashion response capability increased textile exports from EUR 900m to EUR 1.5bn.'
);

-- ── ID 9: Special Economic Zones Reform ──────────────────────────────────────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    9,
    'South Africa''s 11 Special Economic Zones (Coega IDZ, East London IDZ, Richards Bay IDZ, Dube TradePort, Saldanha Bay IDZ, Tshwane Automotive SEZ, Musina-Makhado SEZ, OR Tambo International Airport IDZ, Maluti-a-Phofung SEZ, Atlantis SEZ, and Nkomazi SEZ) have significantly underperformed international comparators. Coega — the oldest and best-resourced — has attracted only 74 enterprises after 24 years. The SEZ Amendment Bill proposes streamlined approvals, investor-led management boards, and a recalibrated incentive package. The deeper structural problems are: high energy costs on-zone, inadequate rail and port connectivity, skills mismatches, and governance failures in zone management entities. Operation Vulindlela''s SEZ workstream is actively driving reform; the Presidency and DTIC are aligned on a performance-based approach.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DTIC tables the SEZ Amendment Bill in Parliament: key provisions include (a) investor-led management board model (minimum 40% private sector board composition), (b) streamlined zone application and investor approval process (maximum 30-day approval timeline), (c) performance-based zone designation renewal, and (d) enhanced SEZ tax incentive (15% reduced corporate tax rate extended to 15 years)","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Department of Trade, Industry and Competition (DTIC) / Parliament"},{"step":2,"description":"Parliament passes the SEZ Amendment Act; DTIC publishes revised SEZ Regulations under the amended Act specifying investor licensing procedures, incentive application process, and performance benchmarks for zone management entities","timeline":"Q4 2025","responsible_party":"DTIC / Parliament / National Assembly Portfolio Committee on Trade, Industry and Competition"},{"step":3,"description":"DTIC initiates a performance audit of all 11 SEZs against a revised scorecard (number of enterprises, jobs, investment value, export revenues, local content); designate underperforming zones for restructuring under new management board model within 12 months","responsible_party":"DTIC / SEZ Board / National Treasury","timeline":"Q1–Q3 2026"},{"step":4,"description":"Priority zone transformation: Coega IDZ restructuring — reconstitute the Coega Development Corporation board with private sector majority; negotiate with Transnet on dedicated Port Elizabeth berth allocation for zone cargo; resolve electricity tariff with Eskom for competitive on-site industrial supply; target 50 new enterprise investments within 24 months","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q2 2028","responsible_party":"Coega Development Corporation / DTIC / Transnet / Eskom"},{"step":5,"description":"Introduce a One-Stop-Shop Investment Facilitation Service in all SEZs: single-window system for environmental authorisations (NEMA), municipal approvals, SARS customs registration, and labour compliance; integrate with InvestSA''s eServices platform and CIPC","timeline":"Q3 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / InvestSA / DFFE / SARS / CIPC"},{"step":6,"description":"SEZ-AfCFTA Integration Programme: designate three SEZs (Coega, Dube TradePort, Richards Bay) as AfCFTA Export Processing Zones with enhanced preferential treatment for goods meeting AfCFTA rules of origin; negotiate AfCFTA-compatible zone incentives with AfCFTA Secretariat","timeline":"Q1 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / DIRCO / AfCFTA NIC"},{"step":7,"description":"Annual SEZ Investment Performance Report: DTIC publishes comparative zone performance data (investment, jobs, exports, enterprises) against international benchmarks (Hawassa Ethiopia, Penang Malaysia, CEPZ Bangladesh); report to Portfolio Committee and Cabinet Economic Cluster","timeline":"Annual from Q1 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / National Treasury"}]',
    '2025–2030; SEZ Amendment Act by Q4 2025; zone restructuring 2026–2028; measurable investment uptick by 2027',
    'R8 billion public commitment over 5 years: zone infrastructure upgrades (R4bn, DTIC and provincial governments), on-zone energy infrastructure (R2bn, Eskom/DMRE), InvestSA one-stop-shop platform (R200m), performance audit and restructuring (R150m)',
    'Special Economic Zones Act 16 of 2014 (amendment — SEZ Amendment Bill required); Income Tax Act 58 of 1962 (Section 12R/12S amendment for extended 15% corporate tax rate); Municipal Systems Act (amendment to allow streamlined municipal approvals within zone boundaries); possibly the Customs and Excise Act for enhanced zone customs facilitation',
    'The SEZ Amendment Bill is the primary vehicle. It is a Section 75 bill (national economic matter) — straightforward parliamentary process. The Income Tax Act amendment for the corporate tax rate extension requires a Taxation Laws Amendment Bill, typically introduced by National Treasury in October of each year. The One-Stop-Shop administrative integration can proceed by executive instruction and MoU between agencies — no legislation required. The AfCFTA-compatible zone incentives require a Ministerial determination under the SEZ Act.',
    'High feasibility: Operation Vulindlela explicitly tracks SEZ reform and the Presidency is actively engaged. The SEZ Amendment Bill has broad cross-party support. DTIC Minister has strong political will. The main risk is implementation failure — the same governance problems that produced underperformance in existing zones could recur if management board reform is not genuinely implemented. National Treasury supports performance-based incentive reform. Labour (COSATU/NUMSA) concerns about zone labour standards must be addressed through an explicit zone labour standards annexure to the SEZ Regulations.',
    'Ethiopia Hawassa Industrial Park (2016): Chinese-built, government-operated zone attracted 30+ international textile manufacturers within 3 years; energy (Chinese-funded hydropower) and logistics (dedicated rail link) were the decisive competitive advantages — demonstrating that infrastructure, not tax incentives, drives zone success. Malaysia Penang Industrial Zone (1970s onwards): investor-led board model (Penang Development Corporation), one-stop approval under the Investment Promotion Act, and skills development partnerships with Penang Skills Development Centre generated 70,000 manufacturing jobs and positioned Penang as a global electronics hub. Bangladesh Chittagong EPZ (BEPZA): streamlined labour and investment regulations within zone boundaries, with BEPZA as a single administrative authority, attracted USD 8 billion in FDI and supports 400,000 garment workers. Rwanda Kigali SEZ (2011): small but high-performance zone with full services package, investor-led management, and 100% renewable energy — 85% occupancy within 8 years, demonstrating that quality of zone environment matters more than scale.'
);

-- ── ID 10: Poultry Industry Anti-Dumping and Local Production Expansion ──────────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    10,
    'The South African poultry industry employs approximately 36,000 direct workers and a further 100,000 in the supply chain. It faces structurally uncompetitive imports — primarily mechanically deboned chicken pieces and leg quarters from the EU (at R8/kg landed cost versus SA production cost of R18/kg) and Brazilian whole birds. ITAC administered definitive anti-dumping duties since 2019–2020, but the Poultry Master Plan (2019–2030) is a social compact trading structured import duty relief for domestic investment commitments. The Master Plan commits industry signatories (Rainbow Chicken, Country Bird Holdings, Astral Foods, Sovereign Foods) to 11,600 new jobs by 2030 in exchange for a structured tariff concession schedule. Key enablers are competitive feed grain prices (linked to agriculture and logistics), energy cost reduction, and veterinary biosecurity (HPAI outbreaks are an acute risk).',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"DTIC convenes the Poultry Master Plan Oversight Committee for a 2025 mid-term review: audit investment commitments, job creation, and production expansion against Plan targets; assess whether the tariff concession schedule remains calibrated to industry performance","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Department of Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development (DALRRD) / DTIC / Poultry Master Plan Oversight Committee"},{"step":2,"description":"ITAC conducts a sunset review of existing anti-dumping duties on EU chicken pieces (expiry: 2025–2026): compile injury and dumping evidence; recommend continuation, modification, or additional measures; ensure measures are WTO-consistent under the Anti-Dumping Agreement","timeline":"Q2–Q4 2025","responsible_party":"ITAC / DTIC"},{"step":3,"description":"DALRRD and DTIC negotiate a Feed Cost Compact with the South African Grain Information Service (SAGIS), AFMA (the animal feed association), and major grain traders: introduce a Feed Cost Stabilisation Mechanism (forward purchase facility through the Land Bank) to reduce feed price volatility — feed represents 60% of poultry production cost","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DALRRD / Land Bank / SAGIS / AFMA / DTIC"},{"step":4,"description":"DALRRD strengthens the HPAI (Highly Pathogenic Avian Influenza) biosecurity system: expand the national surveillance network to 120 active monitoring sites; establish a national vaccine reserve; implement an HPAI Rapid Response Protocol with 24-hour response capacity and a producer compensation scheme under the Animal Diseases Act","timeline":"Q3 2025 — ongoing","responsible_party":"DALRRD / National Animal Health Forum (NAHF) / Poultry industry signatories"},{"step":5,"description":"DSBD and IDC launch an Emerging Poultry Producer Fund: R300 million facility providing concessional finance, technical support, and preferential off-take agreements with major integrators for black-owned and smallholder poultry producers; target 1,000 new emerging producers by 2028","timeline":"Q4 2025","responsible_party":"IDC / DSBD / DALRRD"},{"step":6,"description":"DTIC and ITAC implement a Poultry Value Addition Incentive: Section 12I tax incentive application for greenfield or expansion poultry processing plants investing R100m+ in deboning, further processing, and cold chain capacity; target two approved projects by 2027","timeline":"Q2 2026–Q4 2027","responsible_party":"DTIC / ITAC / National Treasury"},{"step":7,"description":"Annual Poultry Master Plan Report: DTIC and DALRRD publish joint performance scorecard covering production volumes, job creation, import penetration, anti-dumping duty utilisation, emerging producer development, and HPAI incident data; report to Portfolio Committee on Agriculture and on Trade, Industry and Competition","timeline":"Annual from Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / DALRRD / Poultry Master Plan Oversight Committee"}]',
    '2025–2030 (Master Plan period); critical anti-dumping sunset review by Q4 2025; 11,600 jobs by 2030',
    'R600 million public and development finance: IDC Emerging Poultry Producer Fund (R300m), Land Bank Feed Cost Stabilisation Facility (R150m), DALRRD HPAI biosecurity enhancement (R100m/year), ITAC investigation costs (R25m)',
    'ITAC anti-dumping sunset review under International Trade Administration Act 71 of 2002 (administrative); Animal Diseases Act 35 of 1984 amendment for HPAI compensation scheme; Income Tax Act Section 12I amendment to include poultry processing in the approved asset list (National Treasury Taxation Laws Amendment Bill)',
    'ITAC anti-dumping sunset review is an administrative process under the ITAA — ITAC Board recommendation and Ministerial approval are required, no parliamentary vote. The Animal Diseases Act amendment for a producer compensation scheme requires a Section 76 bill (affecting concurrent national-provincial agriculture competence) — full NCOP process. The Section 12I tax incentive designation for poultry processing is an administrative approval by DTIC/National Treasury — no new legislation required.',
    'Moderate-to-high feasibility. The Poultry Master Plan is one of DTIC''s more operationally advanced sector compacts. Both ANC and DA support protecting agricultural employment. COSATU affiliated food and beverage workers union (FAWU) actively advocates for the Master Plan. The key political tension is between consumer price interests (cheaper imported chicken) and producer employment interests — the GNU must make a deliberate trade-off decision, which is politically feasible given the 36,000 direct jobs. DALRRD must manage the HPAI risk proactively — an uncontrolled outbreak would undermine the entire investment case.',
    'Brazil ABPA (Brazilian Association of Animal Protein) anti-dumping dispute management (2018–2023): Brazil successfully defended its chicken export competitiveness while managing WTO anti-dumping disputes with 10+ importing countries by maintaining production cost discipline and scale — a case study for SA in understanding the competitive dynamics of Brazilian imports. India poultry sector development (2010–2020): a combination of feed cost stabilisation (minimum support prices for maize), biosecurity investment (National Action Plan for Avian Influenza), and rural smallholder development schemes grew India''s poultry sector from 2 billion birds to 8 billion birds — demonstrating the scale achievable with sustained policy support. Thailand poultry export model: Thai Broiler Processing Exporters Association-led quality upgrading (from fresh to cooked products) enabled Thailand to maintain EU market access after the 2004 HPAI crisis by shifting to heat-treated exports — a model for SA adding value to avoid raw product import competition. Nigeria Poultry Farm Cluster Initiative (2019): NIRSAL-financed smallholder poultry clusters achieving 60% cost reduction through shared feed purchasing and veterinary services — relevant precedent for SA''s emerging producer programme.'
);

-- ── ID 12: Digital Platforms Competition Framework (Buyer Power Regulations) ─────────
INSERT OR IGNORE INTO implementation_plans (
    idea_id, roadmap_summary, implementation_steps, estimated_timeline,
    estimated_cost, required_legislation, draft_legislation_notes,
    political_feasibility_notes, international_precedents
) VALUES (
    12,
    'The Competition Amendment Act 18 of 2018 introduced buyer power provisions (Section 8(4)) targeting abuse of dominance in supply chain relationships, with particular relevance to digital platforms and large retailers. The Competition Commission''s proposed Buyer Power Regulations (gazetted for comment in 2021) were never finalised. Simultaneously, the growing dominance of digital commerce platforms — Takealot (Naspers subsidiary), Amazon Marketplace, and Meta Commerce — requires a dedicated Digital Markets Act creating ex ante obligations for designated gatekeepers. This idea tracks the regulatory gap between the existing Competition Act framework (ex post, case-by-case) and the structural ex ante regulation needed to prevent permanent monopolisation of SA''s digital commerce infrastructure. DSBD is the primary political champion given the direct impact on small business sellers.',
    '[{"step":1,"description":"Competition Commission finalises and publishes the Buyer Power Regulations under Competition Amendment Act Section 8(4): regulations to cover unfair trading practices, retroactive changes to terms, excessive listing fees, search ranking manipulation, and mandatory data access for third-party sellers on designated platforms; formal publication in Government Gazette","timeline":"Q2 2025","responsible_party":"Competition Commission / DTIC"},{"step":2,"description":"DTIC establishes a Digital Markets Policy Task Team (representatives from Competition Commission, National Treasury, DSBD, DCDT, and SARS) to draft a Digital Markets Bill: develop gatekeeper designation criteria, ex ante conduct obligations, and enforcement mechanism; publish a Green Paper for public comment","timeline":"Q3 2025","responsible_party":"DTIC / Competition Commission / DSBD / DCDT"},{"step":3,"description":"Competition Commission initiates investigation into Takealot''s seller practices under the finalised Buyer Power Regulations: focus on listing fee structures, search ranking algorithms, and MFN clause enforcement; publish investigation findings and any consent order or remedies within 18 months","timeline":"Q3 2025–Q1 2027","responsible_party":"Competition Commission"},{"step":4,"description":"DTIC tables the Digital Markets Bill in Parliament as an amendment to the Competition Act: introduce Chapter on Digital Markets with gatekeeper designation (criteria: annual revenues, market share thresholds, multi-sided market dominance), ex ante conduct obligations, and an expedited Digital Markets Tribunal track","timeline":"Q2 2026","responsible_party":"DTIC / Competition Commission / National Assembly Portfolio Committee on Trade, Industry and Competition"},{"step":5,"description":"Parliament passes the Digital Markets Act (amending the Competition Act); Competition Commission publishes gatekeeper designation criteria and designates initial platforms; affected platforms have 6 months to demonstrate compliance with ex ante obligations","timeline":"Q4 2026","responsible_party":"Parliament / DTIC / Competition Commission"},{"step":6,"description":"DSBD establishes a Digital Platform SME Support Programme: provide eligible small business sellers with legal advisory services (for Buyer Power Regulation complaints), market access to alternative platforms, and an e-commerce export facilitation desk linking to AfCFTA digital trade protocol","timeline":"Q3 2026","responsible_party":"DSBD / SEDA / Competition Commission"},{"step":7,"description":"Annual Digital Markets Compliance Report: Competition Commission publishes compliance assessments for designated gatekeepers; DSBD publishes a Small Business Digital Commerce Index measuring market concentration, seller fee structures, and dispute resolution outcomes; report to Portfolio Committee on Trade and DSBD","timeline":"Annual from Q2 2027","responsible_party":"Competition Commission / DSBD"}]',
    'Buyer Power Regulations finalised by Q2 2025; Digital Markets Act by Q4 2026; gatekeeper compliance by mid-2027',
    'R220 million over 4 years: Competition Commission Digital Markets capacity (R40m/year), Digital Markets Bill drafting and task team (R15m), DSBD SME digital support programme (R50m/year from DSBD budget), Competition Tribunal capacity expansion (R25m)',
    'Competition Amendment Act 18 of 2018 (buyer power provisions already enacted — Regulations required to activate); Digital Markets Bill (new legislation amending Competition Act 89 of 1998); Electronic Communications and Transactions Act 25 of 2002 (amendment for platform-to-business contract disclosure requirements)',
    'The Buyer Power Regulations are issued by the Minister of Trade, Industry and Competition under Section 8(4) of the Competition Amendment Act — this is an executive instrument requiring no parliamentary vote, only public consultation and NEDLAC process. The Digital Markets Bill should be structured as a Chapter added to the Competition Act, not a standalone Act, to leverage existing Tribunal jurisdiction. Gatekeeper designation is an administrative determination by the Competition Commission subject to review by the Competition Tribunal. Platform-to-business disclosure requirements under ECT Act amendment can be implemented as a Section 90 regulation by DCDT.',
    'High feasibility for Buyer Power Regulations (already drafted, political will exists). Moderate feasibility for Digital Markets Act (more complex, platform industry opposition). DSBD Minister is the primary champion — strong motivation from small business constituency. Competition Commission has demonstrated independence and capacity. The DA supports competition policy enforcement; the ANC is concerned about digital monopolisation of black-owned businesses on platforms. Platform operators (Naspers/Takealot, Amazon, Meta) will deploy significant lobbying resources against the Digital Markets Bill — DTIC must manage this by framing the legislation as pro-competitive and pro-investment rather than punitive. Operation Vulindlela''s digital economy workstream should formally incorporate the Digital Markets framework.',
    'European Union Digital Markets Act (DMA, effective May 2023): first comprehensive ex ante regulation of digital gatekeepers — designated Alphabet, Amazon, Apple, ByteDance, Meta, Microsoft; initial compliance assessments show material improvements in app store competition and interoperability. United Kingdom Digital Markets, Competition and Consumers Act (DMCCA, 2024): CMA strategic market status designation enabling bespoke conduct requirements — first designations expected for Google Search and Apple iOS by 2025. Australia ACCC Digital Platform Services Inquiry (2020–2022): produced the News Media Bargaining Code (2021) generating A$200m+ in publisher compensation from Google and Meta — demonstrates that regulatory threat alone changed platform behaviour before legislation passed. Germany Bundeskartellamt Section 19a GWB amendment (2021): digital economy-specific abuse of dominance provisions allowed rapid interim measures against Amazon, Apple, Google, and Meta — a template for SA''s Competition Act amendment approach.'
);

COMMIT;
